INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '34ae19be-7839-4d33-855c-e6902d5585c6',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$OpenAPI vs gRPC — When to Swap Your REST Spec for Protobuf$escape$,
  $escape$OpenAPI contracts describe REST endpoints — paths, verbs, request/response shapes using JSON Schema. Protobuf `.proto` files serve the same contract role for gRPC, but enforce a binary wire format and auto-generate type-safe clients across languages. Where OpenAPI uses `$ref` to compose schemas, protobuf uses strongly typed field definitions with explicit field numbers that guarantee backward-compatible evolution without versioning your paths.

gRPC exposes four RPC patterns that OpenAPI's request/response model can't natively express: unary (identical to a REST call), server streaming (one request → N responses; ideal for live feeds or log tailing), client streaming (N requests → one response; chunked uploads), and bidirectional streaming (N:N; chat, collaborative editors).

Reach for gRPC instead of your OpenAPI-backed service when: binary serialization latency matters at scale, you need streaming without bolting on WebSockets, or internal polyglot microservices need generated clients instead of hand-rolled HTTP logic.

OpenAPI stays the right tool for public-facing APIs — browsers and third-party consumers expect REST/JSON. Use gRPC at the service-to-service boundary where you own both ends.$escape$,
  $escape$// service FeedService in feed.proto — replaces your OpenAPI spec for this service
// rpc GetByte(ByteReq) returns (ByteResp);              // unary
// rpc StreamFeed(FeedReq) returns (stream FeedItem);    // server-stream
// rpc Chat(stream Msg) returns (stream Msg);            // bidi-stream

// Go: consuming a server-streaming RPC
stream, err := client.StreamFeed(ctx, &pb.FeedReq{UserId: "u123"})
for {
    item, err := stream.Recv()
    if err == io.EOF { break }
    if err != nil { log.Fatal(err) }
    fmt.Println(item.Title, item.Tags)
}$escape$,
  $escape$go$escape$,
